[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Weal
<hw>Weal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>wele</ets>, AS.
<ets>wela</ets>, <ets>weola</ets>, wealth, from <ets>wel</ets> well. See
<er>Well</er>, <pos>adv.</pos>, and cf. <er>Wealth</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A sound, healthy, or prosperous state of a person or
thing; prosperity; happiness; welfare.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God . . . grant you <qex>wele</qex> and prosperity.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As we love the <qex>weal</qex> of our souls and bodies.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To him linked in <qex>weal</qex> or woe.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Never was there a time when it more concerned the public
<qex>weal</qex> that the character of the Parliament should stand
high.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The body politic; the state; common wealth.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The special watchmen of our English <qex>weal</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Weal
<hw>Weal</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To promote the weal of; to cause to
be prosperous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Beau. &
Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weal-balanced</ent>⟦br⟧
